            "I found comprehensive information about Dean Oliver's Four Factors and their importance in NBA prediction. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Overview of the Four Factors\n\nDean Oliver developed a theory between 2002 and 2004 that changed how numbers and basketball are associated. The four factors are: Effective Field Goal% or eFG% (40%), Turnover Rate or TOV% (25%), Offensive Rebound Rate or ORB% (20%) and Free Throw Rate or FTR (15%).\n\n## Feature Importance & Weights\n\nShooting is the most important factor, followed by turnovers, rebounding, and free throws. However, other analyses have similarly found that eFG%'s importance is closer to 45%.\n\nRecent research has challenged Oliver's original weights. Two analyses suggest that the weights for eFG%, TO%, OReb%, and FTRate should be 43/39/10/8 (StatAthlon) and 46.3/35.1/11.9/6.8 (Squared2020).\n\n## NBA Prediction Accuracy\n\nThe four factors can produce projection models with an accuracy level of approximately 94% in average, with 24% of predictions totally accurate and 61.5% within 2 wins. Additionally, the Adjusted R\u00b2 for a linear regression model using the four factors to predict wins is 0.96.\n\n## Impact on Offensive Rating\n\nA percentage point increase in effective field goal percentage would lead into the largest increase in offensive rating, underlining eFG%'s dominance as the most impactful factor."
