            "Based on the search results, here's what I found about NBA advanced metrics and their importance:\n\n## Key Advanced Metrics Explained\n\n**ORTG (Offensive Rating)** measures points scored per 100 possessions and reflects efficiency regardless of game pace. **DRTG (Defensive Rating)** measures points allowed per 100 possessions, with lower values being better.\n\n**Net Rating (NRTG)** is calculated as ORTG minus DRTG, with positive values showing dominance.\n\n## Advanced vs. Basic Stats: Feature Importance\n\nThe research shows that advanced metrics have significant predictive power compared to basic stats. Analysis of NBA data over 5 years found that ORtg, DRtg, and their net effect in Net Rating, along with eFG%, AST, PTS, and opponent stats, show relationships to win-loss percentage.\n\nBoth ORtg and DRtg are sufficient indicators of playoff and non-playoff teams. Furthermore, there is statistically significant evidence that offensive ratings are higher in teams that make the playoffs.\n\n## Why Advanced Metrics Matter More\n\nWhen comparing ORtg and DRtg to traditional stats like points per game, ORtg and DRtg delve deeper into offensive and defensive efficiency. Two players can both score 20 points, but one may take 25 inefficient shots while another needs only 12\u2014a difference in efficiency that is invisible in basic box scores."
