            "Based on the search results, here's what I found regarding rolling window features for NBA prediction:\n\n## NBA-Specific Guidance\n\nFor NBA prediction using rolling windows, around the last 20 games is the longest to consider, and around the last 5 games is the shortest to consider. The reasoning is practical: you don't want to have too few games, otherwise your moving average can get easily skewed by outliers, and you don't want too many games or else your moving average won't be sensitive enough to changes teams have made, such as trades, injuries, etc.\n\nOne analysis found that with window lengths shorter than 9, there can be smaller bias, but error increases sharply and correlation drops off pretty quickly, with SMA10 and SMA8 being similar choices to SMA9 for NBA pace prediction.\n\n## General Rolling Window Principles\n\nMore broadly, you can use a short rolling window size for data collected in short intervals and a larger size for data collected in longer intervals, with longer rolling window sizes tending to yield smoother rolling window estimates than shorter sizes.\n\nOne crucial consideration is picking the size of the window for the rolling window method\u2014often you can get a good idea from the domain, and users can also do a parameter search on the window size.\n\n## Window Size Selection Trade-off\n\nThere is a trade-off between variance (shorter windows yield noisier estimates) and bias (longer windows are slower to detect change), and selection should use domain knowledge, information criteria, cross-validation, or sensitivity analysis.\n\nFor your specific comparison (5 vs 10 vs 20 games), the research suggests 9-10 games appears to be a good middle ground for NBA prediction, balancing sensitivity to team changes with stability."
